\b How do I change the pitch of an individual notehead within a chord?\

\b0 \
This is in the tutorial, actually.   Hold down the Alt key.  Now click on the notehead, and holding the mouse button down, drag the notehead up or down to the desired pitch. This is called 'Alt-dragging'.  Notice that the entire chord is selected while you are doing this, and that the chord automatically changes its configuration to the correct one as the notehead is dragged up and down.\
\
\

\b The indentation of new systems reverts to 0 with every new system .  How can  I set indentation once for the entire document?\

\b0 \
Calliope provides several kinds of indentations.  Using the appropriate one for the job is the key to easy formatting.  The indentations given in the System Inspector affect only systems on an invividual basis, and are expected to be used in exceptional situations such as at the beginning of a document to show, for example, the prefatory staves.  To set the indentation for a range of pages of the document, use the Page Format Inspector.  There is a Page Format marker for the first system of the piece.  Command-click on the page format marker to bring up the Page Format Inspector, on which suitable alterations can be made to the margins.  The desired page format stays in effect for all subsequent pages until a system is found with a Page Format marker.   You can add new Page Format markers whenever you wish to begin a new section of the document that has different page format.  System indentations are added to whatever the Page Format margins are.\
\
\

